{"type":"message","id":"1eb5963a","parentId":"afd3b209","timestamp":"2026-02-17T05:09:52.698Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","thinkingSignature":"{\"id\":\"rs_0b39f6bc9ae76092016993f815a8908194be12a5fad30a73cc\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABpk_gX7hPLz6LP1m4JrBlsOX0FyJDWmPVpCCU7-4Mt5jZGbT7fhqS9YXt6H-RwdGZKU7N5ydBFIy_x6FijkqY7JTLkpKRQJNbrMyc-tOW8hgoxLofKpegx-mMID6fhFkB9XP589GeggqRW05LIBOGlPKXcdx_87hs43KmNWKh543ks52Fx-j_d-2X-v4MhBOCCbcC1Pr0LTUHqpcAVngbBhfJk03DiIqL5PQCcuv_j_S8oEvc067tU3BHzYnOypj9SgvzXv2On4YC3KOisgcQI7VpqGG92xC9qn1iJuJgFen6fvpu_SexX-ta1XJ53c15HZAyfwVU5OGAtLKOw8J3ZOByfHz8ddVroD39Dz2fEBdWsOZgiKWLDI_WQpqn6uoY-QktlCQR3y2a-uydhUhVR94pySEny1ah8os5i4X-UDcPJZZdSAxrAw4a8Zndrkbfevo8z6Q5uMKcj0BkLGblCc-rhzNZDBBKxsYuSc3BzHo0833QpEgy0Oeg9bQYVFs2I7Wq2DsUSihVWAy20avxzEni2NXyGgnz4BcvlPVCpsR07LJSpfWTr9QQIaWYO2NmIQX-75ERkYqkH10zGqYKCYcdIWBT3WuBGVAwFFAeFY0KCE-7wh54YQ-0sgE0zXwmonLQ-F_Nawetw5O4i7scdSh-DM5j5Te7GH0u-WVkxXL0t2DWQHc3RMMVHAszVouA8jw9YTqzdJXP_IcWrADkLoaKSi632GwiDbzpa3d_K2dBTYFS-1GrS02IXhdTVpRKVm5f3J_uM6OjWw5TS7vCkjrfbxeYdFDs0mhxxADfa65i1BA3ynJmUkFHS59Y9o0GMmPMbtED7GhvRKAemqmm7TPdYFVrLRPWgo-cMpdwKY_I8GH0hdkB9_pggiuUkYjak6jnVtRwk42F3uaijpaWO9UYAKtvXxc5yp4-5eUGRe-L--HkqzozeeWkpKE5jfSKAm6o6FBmbaFg0lrsKfNevVRdLfg==\",\"summary\":[]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_g0EpfRySOQR5vUILSo4tigZi|fc_0b39f6bc9ae76092016993f81732a88194a7067da2c7277862","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/dossiers/james-turrell.md","content":"# James Turrell\n\n## 5-sentence summary\nTurrell makes light behave like architecture: not illumination of objects, but light as the object. His work trains perception—color fields, skyspaces, and immersive volumes that make you doubt the boundary between seeing and knowing. The craft is engineering-level (space, apertures, controlled luminance) delivered as spiritual calm. For brands, Turrell is the ultimate lesson in *experience design*: the medium is the user’s attention. For Zara, Turrell is how you make “minimal” feel unforgettable—by manipulating light, time, and perception rather than adding graphics.\n\n## Steal this (8)\n1. Design attention, not assets (what the user notices first/last).\n2. Use light as a material in retail/sets/photography.\n3. Slow time: build moments that require waiting to reveal.\n4. Reduce content to increase sensitivity.\n5. Make edges ambiguous (soft boundaries feel premium and modern).\n6. Use color as atmosphere, not decoration.\n7. Create a single immersive thesis per environment.\n8. Respect silence: less messaging, more sensation.\n\n## Concrete modern applications (3)\n- **Apple Store lighting**: controlled luminance + calm material palette.\n- **Wellness/meditation apps**: gradient atmospheres, slow transitions.\n- **Luxury fragrance launches**: light-driven experiential pop-ups.\n\n## Image / visual keywords (3)\n- skyspace\n- color-field glow\n- immersive light chambers\n\n## Primary links (5)\n- https://jamesturrell.com/ — Official site and project documentation.\n- https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/james-turrell — Museum framing + major works.\n- https://www.lacma.org/artists/james-turrell — LACMA artist context (Turrell is LA-linked).\n- https://www.moma.org/artists/5981 — MoMA artist page.\n- https://www.rodencrater.com/ — Roden Crater project site (primary long-form work).\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/dossiers/james-turrell.md\",\"content\":\"# James Turrell\\n\\n## 5-sentence summary\\nTurrell makes light behave like architecture: not illumination of objects, but light as the object. His work trains perception—color fields, skyspaces, and immersive volumes that make you doubt the boundary between seeing and knowing. The craft is engineering-level (space, apertures, controlled luminance) delivered as spiritual calm. For brands, Turrell is the ultimate lesson in *experience design*: the medium is the user’s attention. For Zara, Turrell is how you make “minimal” feel unforgettable—by manipulating light, time, and perception rather than adding graphics.\\n\\n## Steal this (8)\\n1. Design attention, not assets (what the user notices first/last).\\n2. Use light as a material in retail/sets/photography.\\n3. Slow time: build moments that require waiting to reveal.\\n4. Reduce content to increase sensitivity.\\n5. Make edges ambiguous (soft boundaries feel premium and modern).\\n6. Use color as atmosphere, not decoration.\\n7. Create a single immersive thesis per environment.\\n8. Respect silence: less messaging, more sensation.\\n\\n## Concrete modern applications (3)\\n- **Apple Store lighting**: controlled luminance + calm material palette.\\n- **Wellness/meditation apps**: gradient atmospheres, slow transitions.\\n- **Luxury fragrance launches**: light-driven experiential pop-ups.\\n\\n## Image / visual keywords (3)\\n- skyspace\\n- color-field glow\\n- immersive light chambers\\n\\n## Primary links (5)\\n- https://jamesturrell.com/ — Official site and project documentation.\\n- https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/james-turrell — Museum framing + major works.\\n- https://www.lacma.org/artists/james-turrell — LACMA artist context (Turrell is LA-linked).\\n- https://www.moma.org/artists/5981 — MoMA artist page.\\n- https://www.rodencrater.com/ — Roden Crater project site (primary long-form work).\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.2","usage":{"input":1282,"output":527,"cacheRead":23936,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":25745,"cost":{"input":0.0022435,"output":0.007378,"cacheRead":0.0041887999999999995,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0138103}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771304980426}}
