{"type":"message","id":"a16d1bdd","parentId":"aa3374d5","timestamp":"2026-02-17T05:11:53.257Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_DLqcZmShpnPKHbUj7YbR4NcI|fc_0b39f6bc9ae76092016993f88f66f88194bb176befef3406d3","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/dossiers/auralee.md","content":"# Auralee\n\n## 5-sentence summary\nAuralee is “premium basics” done the hard way: obsessive fabric development, calm silhouettes, and colors that look like light on stone. The brand’s minimalism isn’t generic—it’s textile-first, where the surface (hand, drape, density) is the differentiator. Auralee also demonstrates Japanese restraint without austerity: warmth, softness, and lived-in elegance. It’s a reminder that luxury can be quiet if the materials are unmistakable up close. For Zara, Auralee is the lesson that minimal brands win on *sensory proof*.\n\n## Steal this (8)\n1. Put the budget into fabric/material R&D.\n2. Use color like atmosphere: low-saturation, high nuance.\n3. Keep silhouette simple to foreground material behavior.\n4. Make product pages describe texture and hand, not just features.\n5. Build a recognizable “calm palette” that evolves slowly.\n6. Use styling that signals ease, not performance.\n7. Let details be functional (pockets, seams) and impeccably executed.\n8. Photographs should show drape and surface truthfully.\n\n## Concrete modern applications (3)\n- **The Row**: quiet luxury through material and proportion.\n- **COS**: accessible minimalism when elevated by fabric choices.\n- **Hardware products**: soft-touch materials + calm colors as premium cues.\n\n## Image / visual keywords (3)\n- texture-first closeups\n- muted atmospheric palette\n- simple silhouettes, perfect drape\n\n## Primary links (5)\n- https://auralee.jp/ — Official site.\n- https://www.instagram.com/auralee_tokyo/ — Brand visuals and seasonal palette evolution.\n- https://hypebeast.com/tags/auralee — Interviews/coverage index.\n- https://www.ssense.com/en-us/men/designers/auralee — Retail/editorial context and copy.\n- https://www.vogue.com/tag/fashion/auralee — Fashion press trail (seasonal read). \n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/dossiers/auralee.md\",\"content\":\"# Auralee\\n\\n## 5-sentence summary\\nAuralee is “premium basics” done the hard way: obsessive fabric development, calm silhouettes, and colors that look like light on stone. The brand’s minimalism isn’t generic—it’s textile-first, where the surface (hand, drape, density) is the differentiator. Auralee also demonstrates Japanese restraint without austerity: warmth, softness, and lived-in elegance. It’s a reminder that luxury can be quiet if the materials are unmistakable up close. For Zara, Auralee is the lesson that minimal brands win on *sensory proof*.\\n\\n## Steal this (8)\\n1. Put the budget into fabric/material R&D.\\n2. Use color like atmosphere: low-saturation, high nuance.\\n3. Keep silhouette simple to foreground material behavior.\\n4. Make product pages describe texture and hand, not just features.\\n5. Build a recognizable “calm palette” that evolves slowly.\\n6. Use styling that signals ease, not performance.\\n7. Let details be functional (pockets, seams) and impeccably executed.\\n8. Photographs should show drape and surface truthfully.\\n\\n## Concrete modern applications (3)\\n- **The Row**: quiet luxury through material and proportion.\\n- **COS**: accessible minimalism when elevated by fabric choices.\\n- **Hardware products**: soft-touch materials + calm colors as premium cues.\\n\\n## Image / visual keywords (3)\\n- texture-first closeups\\n- muted atmospheric palette\\n- simple silhouettes, perfect drape\\n\\n## Primary links (5)\\n- https://auralee.jp/ — Official site.\\n- https://www.instagram.com/auralee_tokyo/ — Brand visuals and seasonal palette evolution.\\n- https://hypebeast.com/tags/auralee — Interviews/coverage index.\\n- https://www.ssense.com/en-us/men/designers/auralee — Retail/editorial context and copy.\\n- https://www.vogue.com/tag/fashion/auralee — Fashion press trail (seasonal read). \\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.2","usage":{"input":1119,"output":484,"cacheRead":29056,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":30659,"cost":{"input":0.00195825,"output":0.006776,"cacheRead":0.0050847999999999996,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.01381905}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771305101929}}
