{"type":"message","id":"f2cef98a","parentId":"169138cf","timestamp":"2026-02-17T05:12:12.140Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_1vsRYIfvNDpIoKvoL6yc7U5S|fc_0b39f6bc9ae76092016993f89c3a6481949302159424dba99f","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/dossiers/yves-saint-laurent.md","content":"# Yves Saint Laurent (YSL)\n\n## 5-sentence summary\nYSL is sharp elegance with an edge: tailoring, black-as-architecture, and a brand that made modern sexuality legible through clothes. The house built iconic codes (Le Smoking, tuxedo language, sharp shoulders) that are instantly readable and endlessly remixable. Under later eras (including Saint Laurent branding), the lesson becomes how to modernize without losing codes—tight typography, stark imagery, and a controlled palette. YSL also proves that “minimal” can be aggressive, not soft. For Zara, YSL is the template for iconic code discipline: pick a few elements and make them unstoppable.\n\n## Steal this (8)\n1. Build signature codes (shape + palette + attitude) and repeat them.\n2. Use black/white as a system, not a default.\n3. Let typography carry authority (tight, controlled, high-contrast).\n4. Make imagery feel like a stance (not a mood).\n5. Design for recognizability at distance.\n6. Modernize by tightening rules, not by adding novelty.\n7. Keep sensuality sharp—avoid softness unless intentional.\n8. Make hero products into myths (names, stories, rituals).\n\n## Concrete modern applications (3)\n- **Luxury fragrance**: code-driven packaging + stark campaigns.\n- **High-end fashion e-comm**: typographic authority + aggressive whitespace.\n- **Premium nightlife/hospitality**: black-as-brand with tailored details.\n\n## Image / visual keywords (3)\n- Le Smoking silhouette\n- black/white high contrast\n- sharp tailoring geometry\n\n## Primary links (5)\n- https://www.ysl.com/ — Official Saint Laurent site.\n- https://www.fondationpierreberge-yvesstlaurent.org/en — Foundation/museum (primary historical source).\n- https://museeyslparis.com/en — Musée Yves Saint Laurent Paris.\n- https://www.metmuseum.org/collection/search#!?q=Yves%20Saint%20Laurent — Met Costume Institute objects and context.\n- https://www.vogue.com/tag/designer/yves-saint-laurent — Interviews/coverage trail (historical record).\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/dossiers/yves-saint-laurent.md\",\"content\":\"# Yves Saint Laurent (YSL)\\n\\n## 5-sentence summary\\nYSL is sharp elegance with an edge: tailoring, black-as-architecture, and a brand that made modern sexuality legible through clothes. The house built iconic codes (Le Smoking, tuxedo language, sharp shoulders) that are instantly readable and endlessly remixable. Under later eras (including Saint Laurent branding), the lesson becomes how to modernize without losing codes—tight typography, stark imagery, and a controlled palette. YSL also proves that “minimal” can be aggressive, not soft. For Zara, YSL is the template for iconic code discipline: pick a few elements and make them unstoppable.\\n\\n## Steal this (8)\\n1. Build signature codes (shape + palette + attitude) and repeat them.\\n2. Use black/white as a system, not a default.\\n3. Let typography carry authority (tight, controlled, high-contrast).\\n4. Make imagery feel like a stance (not a mood).\\n5. Design for recognizability at distance.\\n6. Modernize by tightening rules, not by adding novelty.\\n7. Keep sensuality sharp—avoid softness unless intentional.\\n8. Make hero products into myths (names, stories, rituals).\\n\\n## Concrete modern applications (3)\\n- **Luxury fragrance**: code-driven packaging + stark campaigns.\\n- **High-end fashion e-comm**: typographic authority + aggressive whitespace.\\n- **Premium nightlife/hospitality**: black-as-brand with tailored details.\\n\\n## Image / visual keywords (3)\\n- Le Smoking silhouette\\n- black/white high contrast\\n- sharp tailoring geometry\\n\\n## Primary links (5)\\n- https://www.ysl.com/ — Official Saint Laurent site.\\n- https://www.fondationpierreberge-yvesstlaurent.org/en — Foundation/museum (primary historical source).\\n- https://museeyslparis.com/en — Musée Yves Saint Laurent Paris.\\n- https://www.metmuseum.org/collection/search#!?q=Yves%20Saint%20Laurent — Met Costume Institute objects and context.\\n- https://www.vogue.com/tag/designer/yves-saint-laurent — Interviews/coverage trail (historical record).\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.2","usage":{"input":617,"output":523,"cacheRead":30080,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":31220,"cost":{"input":0.00107975,"output":0.0073219999999999995,"cacheRead":0.005264,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.013665749999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771305113309}}
