{"type":"message","id":"1f9b27b0","parentId":"001bd58d","timestamp":"2026-02-17T05:12:48.979Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_sJXHgTqN6ydDJ3BQ0VmM7hbv|fc_0b39f6bc9ae76092016993f8c9581c81948d59eb2d4fd406be","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/dossiers/kellogg-on-branding.md","content":"# *Kellogg on Branding* (Tybout / Calkins)\n\n## 5-sentence summary\n*Kellogg on Branding* is the MBA-grade operating manual: positioning, meaning, architecture, extensions, portfolios—the whole machine. It’s not sexy, but it’s the scaffolding that keeps “taste” from collapsing into vibes when money and growth show up. The book is most useful as a shared language for stakeholders: category definition, points of parity/difference, brand equity, and consistency vs adaptation. Its weakness is that it can produce safe, consensus brands if you treat it as a checklist rather than strategy. For Zara, it’s the complement to the art/design influences: the discipline to translate taste into decisions, boundaries, and metrics.\n\n## Steal this (8)\n1. Write positioning as a decision: category + audience + promise + reasons-to-believe.\n2. Separate core equity from campaign expression.\n3. Define points of parity before chasing points of difference.\n4. Manage brand architecture intentionally (house, sub-brands, endorsed).\n5. Treat extensions as equity trades—be explicit about what you spend.\n6. Build internal governance: who approves, what rules, what exceptions.\n7. Measure equity with leading indicators (consideration, trust), not just sales.\n8. Keep a “consistency vs relevance” framework for new channels.\n\n## Concrete modern applications (3)\n- **Scaling startups**: brand architecture and naming as product lines multiply.\n- **Creator brands**: maintain core equity while expanding into new categories.\n- **Retail portfolios**: clarify masterbrand vs line brands to reduce confusion.\n\n## Image / visual keywords (3)\n- brand architecture diagrams\n- positioning frameworks\n- portfolio maps\n\n## Primary links (5)\n- https://www.wiley.com/en-us/Kellogg+on+Branding%3A+The+Marketing+Faculty+of+The+Kellogg+School+of+Management-p-9780471690160 — Wiley publisher page (original edition).\n- https://www.wiley.com/en-us/Kellogg+on+Branding+in+a+Hyper+Connected+World-p-9781119533184 — Wiley publisher page (updated edition).\n- https://www.kellogg.northwestern.edu/ — Kellogg School context.\n- https://www.kellogg.northwestern.edu/faculty/directory/tybout_alice.aspx — Alice Tybout faculty page (authority anchor).\n- https://www.kellogg.northwestern.edu/faculty/directory/calkins_tim.aspx — Tim Calkins faculty page (authority anchor).\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/dossiers/kellogg-on-branding.md\",\"content\":\"# *Kellogg on Branding* (Tybout / Calkins)\\n\\n## 5-sentence summary\\n*Kellogg on Branding* is the MBA-grade operating manual: positioning, meaning, architecture, extensions, portfolios—the whole machine. It’s not sexy, but it’s the scaffolding that keeps “taste” from collapsing into vibes when money and growth show up. The book is most useful as a shared language for stakeholders: category definition, points of parity/difference, brand equity, and consistency vs adaptation. Its weakness is that it can produce safe, consensus brands if you treat it as a checklist rather than strategy. For Zara, it’s the complement to the art/design influences: the discipline to translate taste into decisions, boundaries, and metrics.\\n\\n## Steal this (8)\\n1. Write positioning as a decision: category + audience + promise + reasons-to-believe.\\n2. Separate core equity from campaign expression.\\n3. Define points of parity before chasing points of difference.\\n4. Manage brand architecture intentionally (house, sub-brands, endorsed).\\n5. Treat extensions as equity trades—be explicit about what you spend.\\n6. Build internal governance: who approves, what rules, what exceptions.\\n7. Measure equity with leading indicators (consideration, trust), not just sales.\\n8. Keep a “consistency vs relevance” framework for new channels.\\n\\n## Concrete modern applications (3)\\n- **Scaling startups**: brand architecture and naming as product lines multiply.\\n- **Creator brands**: maintain core equity while expanding into new categories.\\n- **Retail portfolios**: clarify masterbrand vs line brands to reduce confusion.\\n\\n## Image / visual keywords (3)\\n- brand architecture diagrams\\n- positioning frameworks\\n- portfolio maps\\n\\n## Primary links (5)\\n- https://www.wiley.com/en-us/Kellogg+on+Branding%3A+The+Marketing+Faculty+of+The+Kellogg+School+of+Management-p-9780471690160 — Wiley publisher page (original edition).\\n- https://www.wiley.com/en-us/Kellogg+on+Branding+in+a+Hyper+Connected+World-p-9781119533184 — Wiley publisher page (updated edition).\\n- https://www.kellogg.northwestern.edu/ — Kellogg School context.\\n- https://www.kellogg.northwestern.edu/faculty/directory/tybout_alice.aspx — Alice Tybout faculty page (authority anchor).\\n- https://www.kellogg.northwestern.edu/faculty/directory/calkins_tim.aspx — Tim Calkins faculty page (authority anchor).\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.2","usage":{"input":856,"output":609,"cacheRead":31104,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":32569,"cost":{"input":0.001498,"output":0.008526,"cacheRead":0.0054432,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0154672}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771305147432}}
