{"type":"message","id":"d3dd60a4","parentId":"d970880a","timestamp":"2026-02-17T05:16:20.281Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Updating documents concisely**\n\nI need to update YES.md by incorporating citation links while tightening the content. I’ll rewrite each influence into 1-2 bullet points for clarity, and then include a “Refs” link for easy access. The goal is to keep everything concise and well-structured. I’m just trying to ensure it’s clear and informative without overwhelming the reader with too much text. I want to maintain a good balance in the document.","thinkingSignature":"{\"id\":\"rs_0b39f6bc9ae76092016993f97f32608194b1591f844ec43c3f\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABpk_mC8LorVY6VWYTL8TG7QIXGHypHCv7Ux4Lcfd4F4KEsIgb4Hp3eSLzt5DkmulknsHsQSCiMLZjFCVk6iBs2wzXd67tW4WmRoxAvMPhKbcTNKRFSjjXT_X_cwDIKNnkv4a0eFhsPvu36EG4Txo6a3gPfZs6P7JCjLUYiPd_5KZM66zyFAbUBaGDaMMydc8H96jwoOsg80CDrNg3OTH6QgbimEj07LtEmNEhDN-XvoCJofQ5VbcUa5bYqTo0hEYbATlsRViBEKQGRJ5lf5Cb5fMsI-nb89YNvfyC8oRTisI3vpwORCAr4qz9ywhRkT2bkYGwsxHIMnUEXm5dxcUbBNLt4rt0Yb-8v31WDKiros4XZrif2AOWsu-UEF0ZBglBWAW8ZB-T4UQpomdrJOEp1IkWw39Kk4mhcWe6YpRMvf7_3Lm_lg23qnFrZx3Z5Du0zoMViplNQxASl4Gi3mSrs4Lv-6nKnsUEnkigUzA_L1CNC6zQLYjBhrBoCU2QEIlZMbtHV_Lq_Cg784yVCpw6WePrmUkchTfSNPktYdkG0pQlKdTF-bAZJ32zY8_V-uaphdRiYI45tyDVjarvVci_jeqO5Lf2lNuEdJD2PzaPYBgVWjXsPiTneZFvEbt-SWMQfvJBqcWLIYMMsX1hF8tnSuPaFmOllpjfE3A1DlFhmJBWydreRsutC-2oaa2y1y_ePfoE0Hq7HD_7ULFS0eq4GvKPQYcB17-FVymHxyGiOrDRWoNfLVvRM6cmVOgmN15qlZKBCa7gE_HZAkNjT4r5GG0v4798-XApHgRtw1_SA3o0O7fNlfxmo0fOZMdTlQ8WLx3aEo4TI8V_K9Pp5HVtX6Aackx6du1Xz0ZcviNy6DkwBW_RbTlH-E7XQw4_SjRt5P4QHRSrbBh5JzrCLCI33vfaXnTClFHSEcXYn1DldS6xmT01JfA4AY7CGJd3sFe1SI9almL4es8lyZre-XU1OOx6-U9DA_DKWyzIR2XJIAXeFhm124XeDRgR6mqy-UJfTjkCFM1kl4Y8btg4EYmA-nJdR2w==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Updating documents concisely**\\n\\nI need to update YES.md by incorporating citation links while tightening the content. I’ll rewrite each influence into 1-2 bullet points for clarity, and then include a “Refs” link for easy access. The goal is to keep everything concise and well-structured. I’m just trying to ensure it’s clear and informative without overwhelming the reader with too much text. I want to maintain a good balance in the document.\"}]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_EsaAs2kq8kWruJsZ8LmcJEfk|fc_0b39f6bc9ae76092016993f98221f4819494fadf0b3b80a7f0","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/YES.md","content":"# Influences — YES (tight steals + citations)\n\n> Seed list from Josh (2026-02-16). This file is the “actionable” layer; deeper notes live in `dossiers/`.\n\n## Philosophy / Criticism / Theory\n- **Max Bense** — *taste as a system* (entropy/redundancy/signal). Steal: formalize “vibe” into rules you can teach + test.  \n  Refs: https://www.hfg-ulm.info/en/department-head_max-bense.html\n- **Carl Jung** — *archetypes + shadow* for coherent myth and transformation. Steal: define the brand’s role + ritual; name what you refuse to be.  \n  Refs: https://www.junginstitute.ch/en/\n- **Susan Sontag** — *form + ethics*; cut interpretive sludge. Steal: experience-first work; no aestheticizing harm for cool.  \n  Refs: https://www.nybooks.com/contributors/susan-sontag/\n- **Peter Bürger — Theory of the Avant-Garde** — *anti-cosplay filter*. Steal: if you borrow “subversion,” change an institution/operation (authorship, access, participation).  \n  Refs: https://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/theory-of-the-avant-garde\n\n## Graphic / Brand / Industrial Design\n- **Tibor Kalman** — editorial design that takes a side. Steal: concept-first layouts that read like arguments; typography as voice.  \n  Refs: https://www.aiga.org/medalist-tibor-kalman\n- **Naoto Fukasawa** — “without thought” usability. Steal: one dominant gesture; remove seams until use is automatic.  \n  Refs: https://www.naotofukasawa.com/\n- **Kenya Hara** — emptiness as a feature. Steal: restraint with material meaning; whitespace as interface.  \n  Refs: https://www.lars-muller-publishers.com/designing-design\n- **Dieter Rams** — principle-led reduction (ethics, not style). Steal: subtraction + honesty + longevity; build principle checklists into reviews.  \n  Refs: https://www.vitsoe.com/us/about/dieter-rams\n- **Michael Bierut** — systems that ship. Steal: plain-language strategy → typographic identity → templates that non-designers can use.  \n  Refs: https://www.pentagram.com/\n- **Massimo Vignelli** — grid discipline + limited toolset. Steal: fewer choices, higher-quality decisions; manuals that enforce coherence.  \n  Refs: https://www.vignelli.com/\n- **Scott Stowell / Open** — playful intelligence. Steal: one unexpected twist per piece; constraints as idea engines.  \n  Refs: https://notclosed.com/\n- **Peter Saville** — cool framing + controlled ambiguity. Steal: omission as a system; references framed with perfect proportion.  \n  Refs: https://www.petersaville.com/\n- **Bauhaus** — modern design as pedagogy + production. Steal: internal “school” (principles/exercises) + cross-discipline coherence.  \n  Refs: https://www.bauhaus-dessau.de/en/\n\n## Architecture\n- **Mies van der Rohe** — structure-first calm authority. Steal: minimal surfaces demand perfect detail; choreograph space like UX.  \n  Refs: https://www.miesvanderrohe-stiftung.com/\n\n## Fine Art / Conceptual Art\n- **James Turrell** — light as material. Steal: design attention and time; atmosphere as brand asset.\n  Refs: https://jamesturrell.com/\n- **Josef Albers** — color as relationship. Steal: fixed form + controlled variation; palette grammar, not swatch lists.  \n  Refs: https://www.albersfoundation.org/\n- **Henri Matisse** — simplification with joy. Steal: bold flat color + confident contour; cut-out thinking (big pieces).  \n  Refs: https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/henri-matisse-1563\n- **Pablo Picasso** — concept survives formal reinvention. Steal: aggressive iteration; reassemble form to reveal essentials.  \n  Refs: https://www.museepicassoparis.fr/en\n- **Paul Klee** — playful systems. Steal: visual alphabet + grid-under-play; authored symbols that recombine.  \n  Refs: https://www.zpk.org/en/collection\n- **Marcel Duchamp** — framing as authorship. Steal: naming/context/provenance can transform value more than new visuals.  \n  Refs: https://www.philamuseum.org/collections/artist/duchamp-marcel\n\n## Culture / Fashion\n- **Virgil Abloh** — remix + distribution. Steal: citations as content; modular motifs across categories; build a platform that hosts culture.  \n  Refs: https://www.virgilabloh.com/\n\n## Fashion / Heritage Brands\n- **Ralph Lauren** — lifestyle worldbuilding. Steal: cohesive universe + repeatable codes; sell roles/rituals, not items.  \n  Refs: https://www.ralphlauren.com/\n- **A.P.C.** — understatement as identity. Steal: cut/material as signature; quiet typography; repeat purchase rhythm.  \n  Refs: https://www.apc.fr/\n- **Auralee** — texture-forward minimal luxury. Steal: fabric proof + atmospheric color; minimal silhouettes to showcase drape.  \n  Refs: https://auralee.jp/\n- **Yves Saint Laurent (YSL)** — iconic codes + black discipline. Steal: few codes, repeated; sharp typography; elegant aggression.  \n  Refs: https://museeyslparis.com/en\n\n## Information Design\n- **Edward Tufte** — high signal-to-noise. Steal: dense truth; small multiples; annotate claims with context.  \n  Refs: https://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/\n\n## Business / Brand Strategy\n- **Kellogg on Branding (Tybout / Calkins)** — the scaffolding. Steal: positioning + architecture + governance so taste can scale without dilution.  \n  Refs: https://www.wiley.com/en-us/Kellogg+on+Branding+in+a+Hyper+Connected+World-p-9781119533184\n\n## Editorial / Magazines / Publishing\n- **032c** — issue-as-thesis. Steal: high-concept curation + clean modern typography; editorial as brand platform.  \n  Refs: https://032c.com/\n- **i-D** — portrait + scene access. Steal: casting as identity; consistent framing gesture; intimacy over polish.  \n  Refs: https://i-d.co/\n- **The New York Times** — hierarchy at scale. Steal: template rigor + trust mechanics; calm authority under deadline.  \n  Refs: https://www.nytimes.com/\n- **Purple Magazine** — minimal provocation. Steal: negative space as status; selection as the brand; deadpan cool.  \n  Refs: https://purple.fr/\n- **Paper Magazine** — engineered pop moments. Steal: cover-as-event; meme legibility; controlled chaos.  \n  Refs: https://www.papermag.com/\n- **Culture Mag Magazine** (likely **Our Culture Mag**) — always-on cultural radar. Steal: cadence + voice + curation; generous linking/source graph.  \n  Refs: https://ourculturemag.com/\n- **Office Magazine** — contemporary portrait/editorial network. Steal: social-native pacing with clean restraint; series-based publishing.  \n  Refs: https://officemagazine.net/\n\n## Photography\n- **Gregory Crewdson** — cinematic stills with narrative tension. Steal: motivated light + production design; unanswered questions as hook.  \n  Refs: https://www.gagosian.com/artists/gregory-crewdson/\n- **David Hilliard** — intimate triptych storytelling. Steal: sequence creates depth; autobiographical truth with designed composition.  \n  Refs: https://www.davidhilliard.com/\n- **Anthony Goicolea** — psychological surreal staging. Steal: beautiful-but-wrong scenes; identity/doubling motifs with clean craft.  \n  Refs: https://www.anthonygoicoleastudio.com/\n- **Annie Leibovitz** — iconic portrait orchestration. Steal: subject direction + lighting + set as one concept; portraits built to last.  \n  Refs: https://www.vogue.com/contributor/annie-leibovitz\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/references/influences/YES.md\",\"content\":\"# Influences — YES (tight steals + citations)\\n\\n> Seed list from Josh (2026-02-16). This file is the “actionable” la